the predicates ➊ (let it be called P) and ➋ (let id be called Q) are such that P is unary and requires a sequence (ordered set) argument, and for any sequence S, P(S) is equivalent to Q being true of the unpacked argument structure represented by S (for example, if Q is a binary relation, then P([x, y]) is true iff Q(x, y)).

The proposition "what satisfies the predicate ➊" is such that ➋ is in relation ➌ with that proposition. More precisely: considering the predicate ➊, the thing ➋ and the relation ➌: for all X, the proposition that X is an argument structure which satisfies the predicate is true iff the thing is in that relation with the proposition, and furthermore.

The proposition "what satisfies the predicate ➊" satisfies the property ➋. More precisely: considering the predicate ➊ and the property ➋, for all X, the proposition that X is an argument structure which satisfies the predicate is true iff it satisfies the property.

The proposition "what satisfies the property ➊" satisfies the property ➋. In other words: considering the two properties ➊ and ➋, for all X, the proposition that X satisfies the first property is true iff it satisfies the second property, and furthermore, the proposition that X does not satisfy the first property is false iff it doesn't satisfy the second property.
